Excellent 👌 this is a very important Ruby object model concept.

Let’s understand from absolute scratch.

1️⃣ What is respond_to?

Every Ruby object has:

object.respond_to?(:method_name)

It returns:

true → if object can respond to that method

false → if it cannot

Example
class User
  def greet
    "Hello"
  end
end

u = User.new

u.respond_to?(:greet)   # => true
u.respond_to?(:age)     # => false

Simple.

Ruby checks if method exists in:

Object

Its class

Included modules

Superclasses

2️⃣ Now Problem Comes With method_missing

Suppose we do this:

class User
  def method_missing(name, *args)
    "Handled dynamically"
  end
end

u = User.new
u.age        # => "Handled dynamically"

It works!

But now:

u.respond_to?(:age)
# => false ❌

Why false???

Because Ruby checks actual defined methods only.
It does NOT assume method_missing will handle it.

This creates inconsistency.

3️⃣ Enter respond_to_missing?

Ruby provides a hook:

respond_to_missing?(method_name, include_private)

It is automatically used inside respond_to?.

So if you override method_missing,
you should also override respond_to_missing?.

4️⃣ Proper Implementation Example
class User
  def method_missing(name, *args)
    if name.to_s.start_with?("find_")
      "Finding #{name}"
    else
      super
    end
  end

  def respond_to_missing?(name, include_private = false)
    name.to_s.start_with?("find_") || super
  end
end

Now:

u = User.new

u.find_user       # => "Finding find_user"
u.respond_to?(:find_user)  # => true ✅

Now it behaves correctly.

5️⃣ How respond_to? Works Internally

When you call:

u.respond_to?(:age)

Ruby does roughly:

Check method table

If not found → call respond_to_missing?

Return its result

So:

respond_to? → may call respond_to_missing?

But it NEVER calls method_missing.

Important difference.

6️⃣ Why This Matters (Real World)

Frameworks rely heavily on respond_to?:

Rails JSON serialization

Delegators

ActiveRecord dynamic methods

Form builders

API generators

If you override method_missing but NOT respond_to_missing?,
your object behaves incorrectly in meta-programming contexts.

That’s considered bad Ruby practice.

7️⃣ Clean Rule (Interview Gold)

If you override:

method_missing

You MUST override:

respond_to_missing?

That’s the golden rule.

8️⃣ Visual Mental Model

When calling method:

object.some_method
   ↓
Ruby searches method table
   ↓
If not found → method_missing

When calling:

object.respond_to?(:some_method)
   ↓
Ruby checks method table
   ↓
If not found → respond_to_missing?

Two separate flows.

9️⃣ Important: Always Call super

Correct way:

def respond_to_missing?(name, include_private = false)
  condition || super
end

Why?

Because super lets Ruby handle normal cases.

🔟 Final Interview-Level Summary

respond_to? checks if object can handle a method.

method_missing handles undefined method calls.

respond_to_missing? tells Ruby whether method_missing will handle it.

Always override both together.

Always call super.

🎯 Super Simple Explanation

Think like this:

method_missing → actually handles the method call

respond_to_missing? → tells Ruby "Yes, I can handle this"

One does execution.
One does reporting.

